statement:
\textbf{Short answer question. Simplify your answer to the best
possible. Show in detail how you arrive at your answer (work will be
considered for this problem).}

Find the center of mass of the distribution

\begin{align*}\rho(x) = \cos\left(\frac{x}2\right), \quad 0 < x < \pi.\end{align*}

sols:
The centre of mass is given by

\begin{align*}\bar{x} = \frac{I}{M}\end{align*} where

\begin{align*}
I &= \int_0^\pi x\cos\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)\,dx \\
M &= \int_0^{\pi} \cos\left(\frac{x}2\right)\,dx\end{align*}

We start with the simpler integral \emph{M} and use the substitution
\emph{w = x/2}. Then \emph{dw = dx/2}, or equivalently, \emph{dx = 2dw}.
Further, when \emph{x = $\pi$} we have \emph{w = $\pi$/2} and when \emph{x = 0}
we have \emph{w = 0}. The integral \emph{M} therefore becomes

\begin{align*}
M &= \int_0^{\pi} \cos\left(\frac{x}2\right)\,dx \\
&= \int_0^{\pi/2} \cos(w)2\,dw \\
&= \left.2\sin(w)\right|_0^{\pi/2} \\
&= 2\sin(\pi/2)-2\sin(0) = 2.\end{align*}

Next we calculate \emph{I}. This is done using integration by parts:
Choose \emph{u} = \emph{x} and $\displaystyle dv = \cos(x/2)dx$. Then
\emph{du} = \emph{dx} and from the integral we just solve, we know that
$v = \displaystyle 2\sin(w) = 2\sin(x/2)$. Hence

\begin{align*}
I &= \int_0^\pi x\cos\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)\,dx = \left.2x\sin(x/2)\right|_0^\pi - \int_0^\pi 2\sin(x/2)\,dx \\
&= 2\pi - 0 - \left(-\left.4\cos(x/2)\right|_0^\pi\right) \\
&= 2\pi + 0 - 4 = 2\pi-4.\end{align*}

For the second integral we again used our favourite substitution \emph{w
= x/2}. The center of mass is thus

\begin{align*}
\bar{x} = \frac{I}{M} = \frac{2\pi-4}{2} = \pi-2.\end{align*}
